<%- include('../partials/header') %>

<main class="container mt-5">
    <div class="row mb-4">
        <div class="col">
            <h1 class="display-4 fw-bold text-primary"><%= title %></h1>
            <p class="lead text-muted">A professional guide to exploring the rugged trails, dramatic geography, and pristine wilderness of the Peruvian Andes.</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="row align-items-center mb-5">
        <div class="col-md-6">
            <h2 class="h4 mb-3 text-secondary">Geography, Altitude & Climate</h2>
<p>
    At a base elevation of <strong>3,399 meters (11,150 feet)</strong>, Cusco is the gateway to rugged alpine passes like Salkantay and Ausangate. 
    The thin air and dropping atmospheric pressure demand a slow, careful physical pace. 
    Weather here changes rapidly; travelers should prepare for intense sun, sudden freezing winds, and cold downpours all in one day as you transition from humid cloud forests to high-altitude alpine tundra.
</p>

<h2 class="h4 mb-3 text-secondary">Native Flora & Fauna</h2>
<p>
    The Andean trails are rich with unique wildlife, including herds of domestic <strong>llamas and alpacas</strong>, wild vicuñas, and massive Andean Condors soaring over the deep valleys. 
    The landscape is shaped by resilient vegetation uniquely adapted to the high altitude, such as native Ichu grass and ancient Polylepis (Queñua) forests clinging to steep mountain faces.
</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="col-md-6 text-center">
            <img src="/images/cusco-trail.webp" alt="Scenic mountain trail in Cusco Peru" class="img-fluid rounded shadow-sm">
            <div class="mt-2 text-muted small italic">
                <p>Source: Open-source geographic documentation.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</main>

